Â±±Ê∞¥, literally mountain and water, i.e. landscape. Instead ink, brush, and rice paper, rectangles, p5js and screen, explores not code realism, but code-ism composition and form. Áï´, painting, each landscape is performed, unknowing the exact, as is Chinese landscape painting, the painter, paints his or her fictional landscape. Here my code and the hash paints each landscape with a constrained brush, that is rectangles. 

An important aesthetic factor in Chinese landscape painting is the negative space. Here the positive-negative relation is akin to ying-yang, that in Tai-Chi (Â§™Ê•µ), there are no absolute positive-yang and absolute negative-ying. At the edge of one polar extreme, signals the change towards the other. Like midday, the sun will set. And between midday and midnight, there is plenty of grey. 

I am sorry ‚Äúlife has no scores‚Äù will not be my final drop just yet. Precisely since life has no fixed scores to follow. In preparation for my solo ink show in march, I look towards generative art to give me inspiration. Instead of code imitating brush, my brush and mind aims to discover my own fictional landscapes through code and hashes. 

To see mountains, where there are not any, just the concept of them. I hope you enjoy the mountain view as I will. fxhash is more than a community, when our path crosses, we create art together.

metadata.name: YANF #76
metadata.description:
Yet Another Noises and Flows

After three works on landscapes I returned to an abstract work in which I used several kinds of noise fields and a different approach to flow lines.

In this work I use three intermediate images to generate the final image:
- on the first image to each pixels is assigned a color related to the value of the noise field in that point using the main color palette
- on the second image the gradient orientation (angle) of the field is used to assign colors using a secondary palette with the purpose of giving lights and shadows to the final image
- on the third image flow lines are drawn using the direction perpendicular to the gradient, in this way the flows are aligned to the contour lines

After the second and third step the new generated image is blended with the previous giving rise to the final image.

Developed with p5.js

Default resolution: 2400x1600, 1600x2400, 2000x2000 (3/2, 2/3, 1/1 aspect ratio)

[2] to redraw at double resolution (it takes four times then default)
[1] to redraw at default resolution
[s] to save a png at current resolution

Sources of variations are:
- 14 palettes
- 6 kinds of combinations of noise type and fractal type
- 8 kinds of cuts
- 3 kinds of aspect ratio
- 3 border thickness

This Generative Token uses the FastNoiseLite.js and chroma.js libraries.

Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Enfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques #21
metadata.description:
The Enfantines¬†are three sets of beginner piano pieces by¬†Erik Satie, written with the aim of preparing children for the sound patterns of modern music. Composed in 1913, these are genuine children‚Äôs pieces, crafted for small hands, easy to learn. 

‚ÄúEnfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques‚Äù is the second of a set of algorithms that explore the basics of Generative Art, written with the aim of preparing artists for the script patterns of digital life. ‚ÄúEnfantillages Pittoresques‚Äù experiments with predefined plots, colour blending, webgl shaders, and generative music; all with a fresh, childish style. This algorithm has been trained to draw basic shapes in accordance to Satie‚Äôs lyrics. However, it uses them in unusual ways and creates what looks like fantastic creatures, microscopic beings, or, to follow Corneille, Constant, and Appel: "human animals".

‚ÄúIt took me four years to paint like Raphael, but a lifetime to paint like a child‚Äù Attributed to Picasso (falsely, probably)

With two modes that won‚Äôt produce the same outputs, ‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are best experienced twice. In music mode, the code uses Satie‚Äôs piano composition as a way of taming randomness, the sounds affecting the parameters of the strokes.

Hey, these have won me congratulations from the Shah of Persia and the King of Yvetot!


# INTERACTIVITY
Press M or Double Tap (mobile) for AUDIO mode
Wait for SILENT mode
Press I for Trait Info (desktop)
Press 1 for Canvas Save (desktop)

Introduce ‚Äú?pixelDensity=171‚Äù after URL for FULL SCREEN MODE (pseudo-deterministic).
Introduce ‚Äú?pixelDensity=X‚Äù for HQ renders (standard is 2, and 8 produces 400ppi 40x44cm prints).


# EASY-TO-READ CODE
The ‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are educational algorithms. The code has been compressed and minified for a performance boost, but can be read fully in GitHub: https://github.com/ratchitect/


# PERFORMANCE
Better experienced with Chrome.

metadata.name: Attractor #60
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a .png
Press ‚Äôt‚Äô to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Temporal #51
metadata.description:
"Temporal" is a generative (pure code) artwork of abstract colored geometric shapes and forms, mixed in a way that trying to simulate natural media

Technically, colored shapes and curves are drawn in a graphic buffer and my custom fragment shader process and transforms the buffer content into that noisy and scratched output. All are 100% code, no images used.

CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

- P: Change orientation to Portrait with aspect ratio 0.75 (useful eg. for printing)
- L: Change orientation to Landscape with ratio 4/3  (1.333..)
- O: Change orientation to Square (box)
  Due to some 1:1 ratio sensitive calculations, rendering output may differ when switching orientations

----
Made with p5js and custom shaders

ABOUT THE ARTIST
Want to know more ? please read the "SHORT BIO" section here in "Emotions" collection: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/22243

metadata.name: Circumscript #94
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Hyper Pixel #217
metadata.description:
Somewhere between pixel-art and axonometric architectural projections, spatial compositions assembled from multi-resolution pixel precise fragments. 

Hyper Pixel is the result of a continued interest in using projections to represent three dimensional object in  two dimensional picture image, and embracing the fact that all digital images are two dimensional arrays of discrete pixels. In that sense it is also a reaction against both skeuomorphism, or mimicking older media in digital form, and the push towards ever increasing fidelity and resolution. The project uses Military perspective, a form of oblique projection, or 45¬∞ - 45¬∞ axonometric projection, because these angels can approximated fittingly by square pixel grid. 

Press s, m, l, x for exporting an image with increasing resolution.
Press p for pause.
Press r for refresh.

Made with P5.js by @introspect0r

metadata.name: Terraced #65
metadata.description:
terraced craters
towering mountains
tranquil colors
dimetric

* this is an animated artwork, the animation loops, its duration depends on the piece, it can be paused by pressing 'p'
* this is a somewhat interactive artwork, click and drag to rotate around/above the object, scroll to zoom in/out
* the current view can be downloaded by pressing 'd'

I began exploring terraced reliefs 3 years ago, starting with lines and cellular noise, and eventually flat colors that turned into subtle gradients.
During that time, the visual concept oscillated between minimalism and busy images. I dropped the cellular noise, replacing it with 2D simplex noise modifying points on the dual grid.
The result is finally something that produces the iterations that keep me happy, something soothing and quiet. Spend some time with it, see how the light changes the landscape.

Best viewed in landscape mode, 3/2 or 16/9.

metadata.name: The Fringe #90
metadata.description:
We are innately aware of our bodies' position through perception of space. If we are visibly surrounded by walls with flooring under, a ceiling above, and a window facing the sky, we know we are inside of an enclosed space, with a view of outside. But how does a room stopped being an enclosed space? Can a space with 3 walls be considered a room? If we are surrounded by walls but our ceiling is gone, then are we inside or outside? This is an exploration on the edges of our ability to perceive space. The fringes that instill some fear in our mind. And that fear is failing to make sense of our position in a space that slowly loses its tangibility.

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.

created using WEBGL on p5.js

metadata.name: Est #8
metadata.description:
Roll the dice with shapes and capture the moment! 
Est follows Iacta which follows Alea. So here we are now: alea iacta est.

How does it work?

Each Est consists of 64 objects randomly arranged around a center and randomly differing in shape, size, texture, and movement. A curated 6 colors palette is picked and used for the textures. The color palette is sorted by hue, luminosity and/or colorfulness based on the color reference and direction variables.

The animation itself is 32 frames long and stops abruptly. It consists of 3 layers. The first layer moves the objects around the center and draws the animated objects displacing vertex positions and textures coordinates based on modulated sinus waves. Textures are additionally dithered based on a randomized fake 6x6 bayer dither matrix.

The second layer uses the first one and a double buffer to capture the motion blur based on a depth mask.

The third layer is mainly used for screen rendering, debugging and behind-the-scene looks. In addition, postprocessing is performed by shifting the drawing position based on color and center distance.

Features:

- shapes [3] (more s, more m, more l)
- palette [102] (based on YPS magazine covers (Germany), issues 700-750 / 800-850, published 1989 - 1992)
- color sort direction [2] (up, down)
- color sort reference [3] (0, 1, 2) - sorting mode selection

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng Xoshiro128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the same sequence. The animation is synchronized with frames and not with time.

The preview images are taken after 32 frames.

Shortcuts & interactions:

- spacebar to trigger a rotation animation (or single click / tap)
- o to trigger random object change animation followed by a rotation animation (or double click / tap)
- r to trigger a random feature change followed by a random object change and rotation animation (or triple click / tap)
- k to enable the kiosk mode and set the speed (off, 3, 5 or 10 secs)
- m to set the kiosk mode (animate, objects, features (default), special)
- s to toggle the postprocessing screen mode (default, raw, alternative, rasterized, facetes, lineblocks, all) - experimental
- c to capture an image
- f for full screen mode
- h to see all options

Available query string parameters:

- size=8000 - sets the base size for width/height to 8000px (default 3000, useful if you want to capture bigger pngs)
- showannouncement - activates the announcement
- kioskspeed=5 - activates the kiosk mode and sets the speed in seconds
- kioskmode=animate - set the kiosk mode (animate, objects, features (default), special)
- screenmode=default - set the postprocessing screen mode (default, raw, alternative, rasterized, facetes, lineblocks, all) - experimental
- showinfo - activates the info box

metadata.name: Hex-a-Sketch #105
metadata.description:
Truchet tiling with hexagons, drawn with three amounts of sketchiness in p5.js.  I had a lot of fun with this!  I love how it often looks like pastels, and sometimes like crayons.  Sometimes it reminds me of basket weaves or a quilt, or a warm sweater.  The super-sketchy can look chaotic, like it's trying to jump off the page, but if it weren't being made sketchy, then all the tiling would sync together in one form.  The foreground says, "look at me!" But then you notice the background with its nuance and depth.  It's like a dance between the two - the yin and the yang.  

I love sharing what I‚Äôve learned about gen art and inspiring others on my YouTube channel, Steve‚Äôs Makerspace.

After clicking open:
press 2 - 5 to increase pixel density
press s to save a png

Resize goes back to pixel density 1.

metadata.name: Laniakea #62
metadata.description:
This piece captures the mysterious beauty of the Laniakea Supercluster, the colossal cosmic structure that contains our Milky Way galaxy.

A deep black backdrop is scattered with shimmering stars, evoking a sense of endless space and awe-inspiring expanse. Winds of dark matter are captured in the mid-ground, representing the invisible force that drives the formation of the galaxies within the Supercluster.

The foreground features a small spiral galaxy, shining brightly against the backdrop of the universe, reminding us that we are an integral part of an unimaginably grand structure.
